  "prompt": "Will 8 RAC tickets that have changed to CNF, get adjacent berths?",
  "response": "While a change from RAC to CNF (Confirmed) status is great, it **doesn't guarantee adjacent berths** for all 8 passengers.\n\nHere's a breakdown of why and what factors influence berth allocation:\n\n*   **Allocation System:** The berth allocation is done by the Indian Railways' Computerised Reservation System (CRS) closer to the departure time. The system tries to accommodate group bookings together, but it depends on the availability of berths in each coach and the overall occupancy of the train.\n\n*   **Factors influencing berth allocation:**\n    *   **Availability:** The primary factor is the availability of vacant berths in the train. If there aren't 8 adjacent berths, the system will allocate available berths wherever possible.\n    *   **Passenger Details:** Factors like age, gender (senior citizens and ladies are given preference for lower berths), and any disability concessions are considered.\n    *   **Booking Quota:** The quota under which the tickets were booked can also influence the allocation (e.g., General Quota, Ladies Quota, Senior Citizen Quota, etc.).\n    *   **Group Size:** The system tries to accommodate larger groups together, but this becomes harder as the group size increases.\n\n*   **No Guarantee:** Indian Railways **does not guarantee** that all passengers on a single PNR (Passenger Name Record) will get adjacent berths, especially for larger groups.\n\n**Chances of getting adjacent berths are higher if:**\n\n*   The tickets were booked well in advance.\n*   The train is not fully booked.\n*   All passengers are in the same age group and gender (less conflicting preferences).\n\n**What you can do:**\n\n1.  **Check the Chart After Preparation:** Once the final chart is prepared (usually 4-6 hours before departure), check the berth allocation online (on the IRCTC website or app) or on the charts pasted at the railway station.\n2.  **Approach the TTE (Travelling Ticket Examiner):** If you find that the berths are scattered, approach the TTE on the train. The TTE has the authority to make adjustments to the berth allocation based on availability and passenger requests. Be polite and explain your situation. While the TTE can't perform miracles, they might be able to help if there are any cancellations or no-shows.\n3.  **Be prepared for split berths:** If you have 8 passengers, it's likely that you will get separated to some degree if all of your seats are not adjacent.\n\n**In summary, while the confirmation of RAC tickets is a positive step, it doesn't automatically translate to adjacent berths. Check the final chart and speak to the TTE for assistance.**\n",
